# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thermodynamic-modelling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] It is a trace gas in Earth's atmosphere at 428 parts per million (ppm), or about 0.043% (as of July 2025) having risen from pre-industrial levels of 280 ppm or about 0.028%.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Burning fossil fuels is the main cause of these increased CO2 concentrations, which are the primary cause of climate change.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Its concentration in Earth's pre-industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by organisms and geological features.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Plants, algae and cyanobacteria use energy from sunlight to synthesize carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and water in a process called photosynthesis, which produces oxygen as a waste product.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In turn, oxygen is consumed and CO2 is released as waste by all aerobic organisms when they metabolize organic compounds to produce energy by respiration.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is released from organic materials when they decay or combust, such as in forest fires.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in water, it forms carbonate and mainly bicarbonate (HCO3–), which causes ocean acidification as atmospheric CO2 levels increase.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is 53% denser than dry air, but is long-lived and thoroughly mixes in the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] About half of excess CO2 emissions to the atmosphere are absorbed by land and ocean carbon sinks.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] These sinks can become saturated and are volatile, as decay and wildfires result in the CO2 being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] CO2, or the carbon it holds, is eventually sequestered (stored for the long term) in rocks and organic deposits like coal, petroleum and natural gas.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Nearly all CO2 produced by humans goes into the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Less than 1% of CO2 produced annually is put to commercial use, mostly in the fertilizer industry and in the oil and gas industry for enhanced oil recovery.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Other commercial applications include food and beverage production, metal fabrication, cooling, fire suppression and stimulating plant growth in greenhouses.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The symmetry of a carbon dioxide molecule is linear and centrosymmetric at its equilibrium geometry.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The length of the carbon–oxygen bond in carbon dioxide is 116.3 pm, noticeably shorter than the roughly 140 pm length of a typical single C–O bond, and shorter than most other C–O multiply bonded functional groups such as carbonyls.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Since it is centrosymmetric, the molecule has no electric dipole moment.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] As a linear triatomic molecule, CO2 has four vibrational modes as shown in the diagram.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In the symmetric and the antisymmetric stretching modes, the atoms move along the axis of the molecule.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] There are two bending modes, which are degenerate, meaning that they have the same frequency and same energy, because of the symmetry of the molecule.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] When a molecule touches a surface or touches another molecule, the two bending modes can differ in frequency because the interaction is different for the two modes.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Some of the vibrational modes are observed in the infrared (IR) spectrum: the antisymmetric stretching mode at wavenumber 2349 cm−1 (wavelength 4.25 μm) and the degenerate pair of bending modes at 667 cm−1 (wavelength 15.0 μm).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The symmetric stretching mode does not create an electric dipole so is not observed in IR spectroscopy, but it is detected in Raman spectroscopy at 1388 cm−1 (wavelength 7.20 μm), with a Fermi resonance doublet at 1285 cm−1.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In the gas phase, carbon dioxide molecules undergo significant vibrational motions and do not keep a fixed structure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] However, in a Coulomb explosion imaging experiment, an instantaneous image of the molecular structure can be deduced.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Such an experiment has been performed for carbon dioxide.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The result of this experiment, and the conclusion of theoretical calculations based on an ab initio potential energy surface of the molecule, is that none of the molecules in the gas phase are ever exactly linear.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This counter-intuitive result is trivially due to the fact that the nuclear motion volume element vanishes for linear geometries.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This is so for all molecules except diatomic molecules.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is soluble in water, in which it reversibly forms H2CO3 (carbonic acid), which is a weak acid, because its ionization in water is incomplete.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Hence, the majority of the carbon dioxide is not converted into carbonic acid, but remains as CO2 molecules, not affecting the pH.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The relative concentrations of CO2, H2CO3, and the deprotonated forms HCO3– (bicarbonate) and CO32– (carbonate) depend on the pH.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] As shown in a Bjerrum plot, in neutral or slightly alkaline water (pH > 6.5), the bicarbonate form predominates (>50%) becoming the most prevalent (>95%) at the pH of seawater.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In very alkaline water (pH > 10.4), the predominant (>50%) form is carbonate.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The oceans, being mildly alkaline with typical pH = 8.2–8.5, contain about 120 mg of bicarbonate per liter.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] where the denominator includes only covalently bound H2CO3 and does not include hydrated CO2(aq).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Since most of the dissolved CO2 remains as CO2 molecules, *K*a1(apparent) has a much larger denominator and a much smaller value than the true *K*a1.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The bicarbonate ion is an amphoteric species that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH of the solution.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In organisms, carbonic acid production is catalysed by the enzyme known as carbonic anhydrase.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In addition to altering its acidity, the presence of carbon dioxide in water also affects its electrical properties.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in desalinated water, the electrical conductivity increases significantly from below 1 μS/cm to nearly 30 μS/cm.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] When heated, the water begins to gradually lose the conductivity induced by the presence of $\mathrm {CO_{2}}$ , especially noticeable as temperatures exceed 30 °C.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The temperature dependence of the electrical conductivity of fully deionized water without CO2 saturation is comparably low in relation to these data.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is a potent electrophile having an electrophilic reactivity that is comparable to benzaldehyde or strongly electrophilic α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] However, unlike electrophiles of similar reactivity, the reactions of nucleophiles with CO2 are thermodynamically less favored and are often found to be highly reversible.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The reversible reaction of carbon dioxide with amines to make carbamates is used in CO2 scrubbers and has been suggested as a possible starting point for carbon capture and storage by amine gas treating.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In metal carbon dioxide complexes, CO2 serves as a ligand, which can facilitate the conversion of CO2 to other chemicals.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The redox potential for this reaction near pH 7 is about −0.53 V *versus* the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The nickel-containing enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase catalyses this process.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] At low concentrations, the gas is odorless; however, at sufficiently high concentrations, it has a sharp, acidic odor.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] At standard temperature and pressure, the density of carbon dioxide is around 1.98 kg/m3, about 1.53 times that of air.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] At a pressure of 1 atm (0.101325 MPa), the gas deposits directly to a solid at temperatures below 194.6855(30) K (−78.4645(30) °C) and the solid sublimes directly to a gas above this temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In its solid state, carbon dioxide is commonly called dry ice.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Another form of solid carbon dioxide observed at high pressure is an amorphous glass-like solid.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This form of glass, called *carbonia*, is produced by supercooling heated CO2 at extreme pressures (40–48 GPa, or about 400,000 atmospheres) in a diamond anvil.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This discovery confirmed the theory that carbon dioxide could exist in a glass state similar to other members of its elemental family, like silicon dioxide (silica glass) and germanium dioxide.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Unlike silica and germania glasses, however, carbonia glass is not stable at normal pressures and reverts to gas when pressure is released.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] At temperatures and pressures above the critical point, carbon dioxide behaves as a supercritical fluid known as supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is an end product of cellular respiration in organisms that obtain energy by breaking down sugars, fats and amino acids with oxygen as part of their metabolism.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This includes all plants, algae and animals and aerobic fungi and bacteria.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In vertebrates, the carbon dioxide travels in the blood from the body's tissues to the skin (e.g., amphibians) or the gills (e.g., fish), from where it dissolves in the water, or to the lungs from where it is exhaled.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] During active photosynthesis, plants can absorb more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than they release in respiration.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon fixation is a biochemical process by which atmospheric carbon dioxide is incorporated by plants, algae and cyanobacteria into energy-rich organic molecules such as glucose, thus creating their own food by photosynthesis.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Photosynthesis uses carbon dioxide and water to produce sugars from which other organic compounds can be constructed, and oxygen is produced as a by-product.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase oxygenase, commonly abbreviated to RuBisCO, is the enzyme involved in the first major step of carbon fixation, the production of two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate from CO2 and ribulose bisphosphate, as shown in the diagram at left.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] RuBisCO is thought to be the single most abundant protein on Earth.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Phototrophs use the products of their photosynthesis as internal food sources and as raw material for the biosynthesis of more complex organic molecules, such as polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and proteins.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] These are used for their own growth, and also as the basis of the food chains and webs that feed other organisms, including animals such as ourselves.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Some important phototrophs, the coccolithophores synthesise hard calcium carbonate scales.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] A globally significant species of coccolithophore is *Emiliania huxleyi* whose calcite scales have formed the basis of many sedimentary rocks such as limestone, where what was previously atmospheric carbon can remain fixed for geological timescales.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Plants can grow as much as 50% faster in concentrations of 1,000 ppm CO2 when compared with ambient conditions, though this assumes no change in climate and no limitation on other nutrients.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Elevated CO2 levels cause increased growth reflected in the harvestable yield of crops, with wheat, rice and soybean all showing increases in yield of 12–14% under elevated CO2 in FACE experiments.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations result in fewer stomata developing on plants which leads to reduced water usage and increased water-use efficiency.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Studies using FACE have shown that CO2 enrichment leads to decreased concentrations of micronutrients in crop plants.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This may have knock-on effects on other parts of ecosystems as herbivores will need to eat more food to gain the same amount of protein.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The concentration of secondary metabolites such as phenylpropanoids and flavonoids can also be altered in plants exposed to high concentrations of CO2.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Plants also emit CO2 during respiration, and so the majority of plants and algae, which use C3 photosynthesis, are only net absorbers during the day.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Though a growing forest will absorb many tons of CO2 each year, a mature forest will produce as much CO2 from respiration and decomposition of dead specimens (e.g., fallen branches) as is used in photosynthesis in growing plants.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Contrary to the long-standing view that they are carbon neutral, mature forests can continue to accumulate carbon and remain valuable carbon sinks, helping to maintain the carbon balance of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Additionally, and crucially to life on earth, photosynthesis by phytoplankton consumes dissolved CO2 in the upper ocean and thereby promotes the absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide content in fresh air (averaged between sea-level and 10 kPa level, i.e., about 30 km (19 mi) altitude) varies between 0.036% (360 ppm) and 0.041% (412 ppm), depending on the location.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In humans, exposure to CO2 at concentrations greater than 5% causes the development of hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of 7% to 10% (70,000 to 100,000 ppm) may cause suffocation, even in the presence of sufficient oxygen, manifesting as dizziness, headache, visual and hearing dysfunction, and unconsciousness within a few minutes to an hour.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of more than 10% may cause convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] CO2 levels of more than 30% act rapidly leading to loss of consciousness in seconds.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carrion feeders attracted to the carcasses are then also killed.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Children have been killed in the same way near the city of Goma by CO2 emissions from the nearby volcano Mount Nyiragongo.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The Swahili term for this phenomenon is *mazuku*.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Adaptation to increased concentrations of CO2 occurs in humans, including modified breathing and kidney bicarbonate production, in order to balance the effects of blood acidification (acidosis).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Several studies suggested that 2.0 percent inspired concentrations could be used for closed air spaces (e.g. a submarine) since the adaptation is physiological and reversible, as deterioration in performance or in normal physical activity does not happen at this level of exposure for five days.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Yet, other studies show a decrease in cognitive function even at much lower levels.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Also, with ongoing respiratory acidosis, adaptation or compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse the condition.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] There are few studies of the health effects of long-term continuous CO2 exposure on humans and animals at levels below 1%.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Occupational CO2 exposure limits have been set in the United States at 0.5% (5000 ppm) for an eight-hour period.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] At this CO2 concentration, International Space Station crew experienced headaches, lethargy, mental slowness, emotional irritation, and sleep disruption.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Studies in animals at 0.5% CO2 have demonstrated kidney calcification and bone loss after eight weeks of exposure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] A study of humans exposed in 2.5 hour sessions demonstrated significant negative effects on cognitive abilities at concentrations as low as 0.1% (1000 ppm) CO2 likely due to CO2 induced increases in cerebral blood flow.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Another study observed a decline in basic activity level and information usage at 1000 ppm, when compared to 500 ppm.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] However a review of the literature found that a reliable subset of studies on the phenomenon of carbon dioxide induced cognitive impairment to only show a small effect on high-level decision making (for concentrations below 5000 ppm).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Most of the studies were confounded by inadequate study designs, environmental comfort, uncertainties in exposure doses and differing cognitive assessments used.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Similarly a study on the effects of the concentration of CO2 in motorcycle helmets has been criticized for having dubious methodology in not noting the self-reports of motorcycle riders and taking measurements using mannequins.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Further when normal motorcycle conditions were achieved (such as highway or city speeds) or the visor was raised the concentration of CO2 declined to safe levels (0.2%).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Poor ventilation is one of the main causes of excessive CO2 concentrations in closed spaces, leading to poor indoor air quality.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide differential above outdoor concentrations at steady state conditions (when the occupancy and ventilation system operation are sufficiently long that CO2 concentration has stabilized) are sometimes used to estimate ventilation rates per person.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Higher CO2 concentrations are associated with occupant health, comfort and performance degradation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] ASHRAE Standard 62.1–2007 ventilation rates may result in indoor concentrations up to 2,100 ppm above ambient outdoor conditions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Thus if the outdoor concentration is 400 ppm, indoor concentrations may reach 2,500 ppm with ventilation rates that meet this industry consensus standard.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations in poorly ventilated spaces can be found even higher than this (range of 3,000 or 4,000 ppm).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Miners, who are particularly vulnerable to gas exposure due to insufficient ventilation, referred to mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen as "blackdamp", "choke damp" or "stythe".
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Before more effective technologies were developed, miners would frequently monitor for dangerous levels of blackdamp and other gases in mine shafts by bringing a caged canary with them as they worked.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The canary is more sensitive to asphyxiant gases than humans, and as it became unconscious would stop singing and fall off its perch.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The Davy lamp could also detect high levels of blackdamp (which sinks, and collects near the floor) by burning less brightly, while methane, another suffocating gas and explosion risk, would make the lamp burn more brightly.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In February 2020, three people died from suffocation at a party in Moscow when dry ice (frozen CO2) was added to a swimming pool to cool it down.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] A similar accident occurred in 2018 when a woman died from CO2 fumes emanating from the large amount of dry ice she was transporting in her car.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Humans spend more and more time in a confined atmosphere (around 80-90% of the time in a building or vehicle).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In homes, schools, nurseries and offices, there are no systematic relationships between the levels of CO2 and other pollutants, and indoor CO2 is statistically not a good predictor of pollutants linked to outdoor road (or air, etc.) traffic.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is the parameter that changes the fastest (with hygrometry and oxygen levels when humans or animals are gathered in a closed or poorly ventilated room).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In poor countries, many open hearths are sources of CO2 and CO emitted directly into the living environment.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Local concentrations of carbon dioxide can reach high values near strong sources, especially those that are isolated by surrounding terrain.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] At the Bossoleto hot spring near Rapolano Terme in Tuscany, Italy, situated in a bowl-shaped depression about 100 m (330 ft) in diameter, concentrations of CO2 rise to above 75% overnight, sufficient to kill insects and small animals.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] After sunrise the gas is dispersed by convection.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] High concentrations of CO2 produced by disturbance of deep lake water saturated with CO2 are thought to have caused 37 fatalities at Lake Monoun, Cameroon in 1984 and 1700 casualties at Lake Nyos, Cameroon in 1986.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The body produces approximately 2.3 pounds (1.0 kg) of carbon dioxide per day per person, containing 0.63 pounds (290 g) of carbon.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In humans, this carbon dioxide is carried through the venous system and is breathed out through the lungs, resulting in lower concentrations in the arteries.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The carbon dioxide content of the blood is often given as the partial pressure, which is the pressure which carbon dioxide would have had if it alone occupied the volume.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In humans, the blood carbon dioxide contents are shown in the adjacent table.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is carried in blood in three different ways.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Exact percentages vary between arterial and venous blood.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Hemoglobin, the main oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, carries both oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] However, the CO2 bound to hemoglobin does not bind to the same site as oxygen.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Instead, it combines with the N-terminal groups on the four globin chains.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] However, because of allosteric effects on the hemoglobin molecule, the binding of CO2 decreases the amount of oxygen that is bound for a given partial pressure of oxygen.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This is known as the Haldane Effect, and is important in the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Conversely, a rise in the partial pressure of CO2 or a lower pH will cause offloading of oxygen from hemoglobin, which is known as the Bohr effect.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is one of the mediators of local autoregulation of blood supply.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] If its concentration is high, the capillaries expand to allow a greater blood flow to that tissue.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Bicarbonate ions are crucial for regulating blood pH.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] A person's breathing rate influences the level of CO2 in their blood.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Breathing that is too slow or shallow causes respiratory acidosis, while breathing that is too rapid leads to hyperventilation, which can cause respiratory alkalosis.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Although the body requires oxygen for metabolism, low oxygen levels normally do not stimulate breathing.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Rather, breathing is stimulated by higher carbon dioxide levels.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] As a result, breathing low-pressure air or a gas mixture with no oxygen at all (such as pure nitrogen) can lead to loss of consciousness without ever experiencing air hunger.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This is especially perilous for high-altitude fighter pilots.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] It is also why flight attendants instruct passengers, in case of loss of cabin pressure, to apply the oxygen mask to themselves first before helping others; otherwise, one risks losing consciousness.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The respiratory centers try to maintain an arterial CO2 pressure of 40 mmHg.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] With intentional hyperventilation, the CO2 content of arterial blood may be lowered to 10–20 mmHg (the oxygen content of the blood is little affected), and the respiratory drive is diminished.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This is why one can hold one's breath longer after hyperventilating than without hyperventilating.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This carries the risk that unconsciousness may result before the need to breathe becomes overwhelming, which is why hyperventilation is particularly dangerous before free diving.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The current increase in CO2 concentrations is primarily driven by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Other significant human activities that emit CO2 include cement production, deforestation, and biomass burning.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 and other long-lived greenhouse gases such as methane increase the absorption and emission of infrared radiation by the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This has led to a rise in average global temperature and ocean acidification.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Another direct effect is the CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 causes a range of further effects of climate change on the environment and human living conditions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] It absorbs and emits infrared radiation at its two infrared-active vibrational frequencies.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The two wavelengths are 4.26 μm (2,347 cm−1) (antisymmetric stretching vibrational mode) and 14.99 μm (667 cm−1) (bending vibrational mode).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] CO2 plays a significant role in influencing Earth's surface temperature through the greenhouse effect.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Light emission from the Earth's surface is most intense in the infrared region between 200 and 2500 cm−1, as opposed to light emission from the much hotter Sun which is most intense in the visible region.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Absorption of infrared light at the vibrational frequencies of atmospheric CO2 traps energy near the surface, warming the surface of Earth and its lower atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Less energy reaches the upper atmosphere, which is therefore cooler because of this absorption.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The present atmospheric concentration of CO2 is the highest for 14 million years.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere were as high as 4,000 ppm during the Cambrian period about 500 million years ago, and as low as 180 ppm during the Quaternary glaciation of the last two million years.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Reconstructed temperature records for the last 420 million years indicate that atmospheric CO2 concentrations peaked at approximately 2,000 ppm.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This peak happened during the Devonian period (400 million years ago).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Another peak occurred in the Triassic period (220–200 million years ago).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide dissolves in the ocean to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), bicarbonate (HCO3–), and carbonate (CO32–).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] There is about fifty times as much carbon dioxide dissolved in the oceans as exists in the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The oceans act as an enormous carbon sink, and have taken up about a third of CO2 emitted by human activity.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in the pH of the Earth's ocean.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) levels exceeding 422 ppm (as of 2024).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This chemical reaction produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO−3) and a hydrogen ion (H+).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The presence of free hydrogen ions (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean, increasing acidity (this does not mean that seawater is acidic yet; it is still alkaline, with a pH higher than 8).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Marine calcifying organisms, such as mollusks and corals, are especially vulnerable because they rely on calcium carbonate to build shells and skeletons.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] A change in pH by 0.1 represents a 26% increase in hydrogen ion concentration in the world's oceans (the pH scale is logarithmic, so a change of one in pH units is equivalent to a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Sea-surface pH and carbonate saturation states vary depending on ocean depth and location.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Colder and higher latitude waters are capable of absorbing more CO2.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This can cause acidity to rise, lowering the pH and carbonate saturation levels in these areas.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Several other factors influence the atmosphere-ocean CO2 exchange, and thus local ocean acidification.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] These include ocean currents and upwelling zones, proximity to large continental rivers, sea ice coverage, and atmospheric exchange with nitrogen and sulfur from fossil fuel burning and agriculture.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Changes in ocean chemistry can have extensive direct and indirect effects on organisms and their habitats.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] One of the most important repercussions of increasing ocean acidity relates to the production of shells out of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] This process is called calcification and is important to the biology and survival of a wide range of marine organisms.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Calcification involves the precipitation of dissolved ions into solid CaCO3 structures, structures for many marine organisms, such as coccolithophores, foraminifera, crustaceans, mollusks, etc.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] After they are formed, these CaCO3 structures are vulnerable to dissolution unless the surrounding seawater contains saturating concentrations of carbonate ions (CO2−3).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Very little of the extra carbon dioxide that is added into the ocean remains as dissolved carbon dioxide.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The majority dissociates into additional bicarbonate and free hydrogen ions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] To maintain chemical equilibrium, some of the carbonate ions already in the ocean combine with some of the hydrogen ions to make further bicarbonate.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is also introduced into the oceans through hydrothermal vents.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The *Champagne* hydrothermal vent, found at the Northwest Eifuku volcano in the Mariana Trench, produces almost pure liquid carbon dioxide, one of only two known sites in the world as of 2004, the other being in the Okinawa Trough.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/carbon-dioxide] The finding of a submarine lake of liquid carbon dioxide in the Okinawa Trough was reported in 2006.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] In computational chemistry and molecular dynamics, the **combination rules** or **combining rules** are equations that provide the interaction energy between two dissimilar non-bonded atoms, usually for the part of the potential representing the van der Waals interaction.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] In the simulation of mixtures, the choice of combining rules can sometimes affect the outcome of the simulation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] The Lennard-Jones Potential is a mathematically simple model for the interaction between a pair of atoms or molecules.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] where *ε* is the depth of the potential well, *σ* is the finite distance at which the inter-particle potential is zero, *r* is the distance between the particles.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] The potential reaches a minimum, of depth *ε*, when *r* = 21/6σ ≈ 1.122σ.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] The Lorentz rule is only analytically correct for hard sphere systems.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] Intuitively, since $\sigma _{i},\sigma _{j}$ loosely reflect the radii of particle i and j respectively, their averages can be said to be the effective radii between the two particles at which point repulsive interactions become severe.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] Physically, this arises from the fact that $\epsilon$ is related to the induced dipole interactions between two particles.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] Given two particles with instantaneous dipole $\mu _{i},\mu _{j}$ respectively, their interactions correspond to the products of $\mu _{i},\mu _{j}$ .
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] An arithmetic average of $\epsilon _{i}$ and $\epsilon _{j}$ will not however, result in the average of the two dipole products, but the average of their logarithms would be.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] These rules are the most widely used and are the default in many molecular simulation packages, but are not without failings.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] Many others have been proposed, including those of Tang and Toennies Pena, Hudson and McCoubrey and Sikora (1970).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] Other rules for that have been proposed for the Exp-6 potential are the Mason-Rice rules and the Srivastava and Srivastava rules (1956).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] Industrial equations of state have similar mixing and combining rules.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/combining-rules] There is also the Huron-Vidal mixing rule, and the more complex Wong-Sandler mixing rule, which equates excess Helmholtz free energy at infinite pressure between an equation of state and an activity coefficient model (and thus with liquid excess Gibbs free energy).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Cubic equations of state are a specific class of thermodynamic models for modeling the pressure of a gas as a function of temperature and density and which can be rewritten as a cubic function of the molar volume.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Equations of state are generally applied in the fields of physical chemistry and chemical engineering, particularly in the modeling of vapor–liquid equilibrium and chemical engineering process design.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] where T is the absolute temperature, p is the pressure, $V_{\text{m}}$ is the molar volume and R is the universal gas constant.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Note that $V_{\text{m}}=V/n$ , where V is the volume, and $n=N/N_{\text{A}}$ , where n is the number of moles, N is the number of particles, and $N_{\text{A}}$ is the Avogadro constant.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] These definitions apply to all equations of state below as well.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Proposed in 1873, the van der Waals equation of state was one of the first to perform markedly better than the ideal gas law.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] In this equation, usually a is called the attraction parameter and b the repulsion parameter (or the effective molecular volume).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] While the equation is definitely superior to the ideal gas law and does predict the formation of a liquid phase, the agreement with experimental data for vapor-liquid equilibria is limited.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The van der Waals equation is commonly referenced in textbooks and papers for historical and other reasons, but since its development other equations of only slightly greater complexity have been since developed, many of which are far more accurate.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The van der Waals equation may be considered as an ideal gas law which has been "improved" by the inclusion of two non-ideal contributions to the equation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] While ideal gas molecules do not interact, real molecules will exhibit attractive van der Waals forces if they are sufficiently close together.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The attractive forces, which are proportional to the density $\rho$ , tend to retard the collisions that molecules have with the container walls and lower the pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The number of collisions that are so affected is also proportional to the density.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Thus, the pressure is lowered by an amount proportional to $\rho ^{2}$ , or inversely proportional to the squared molar volume.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Expressions for $(a,b)$ written as functions of $(T_{\text{c}},p_{\text{c}})$ may also be obtained and are often used to parameterize the equation because the critical temperature and pressure are readily accessible to experiment.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] For $P_{\text{r}}<1$ and $T_{\text{r}}<1$ , the system is in a state of vapor–liquid equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] In that situation, the reduced cubic equation of state yields 3 solutions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The largest and the lowest solution are the gas and liquid reduced volume.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] In this situation, the Maxwell construction is sometimes used to model the pressure as a function of molar volume.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The compressibility factor $Z=PV_{\text{m}}/RT$ is often used to characterize non-ideal behavior.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Introduced in 1949, the Redlich–Kwong equation of state was considered to be a notable improvement to the van der Waals equation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] It is still of interest primarily due to its relatively simple form.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] While superior to the van der Waals equation in some respects, it performs poorly with respect to the liquid phase and thus cannot be used for accurately calculating vapor–liquid equilibria.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] However, it can be used in conjunction with separate liquid-phase correlations for this purpose.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The Redlich–Kwong equation is consistent with the theorem of corresponding states.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] This is an improvement over the van der Waals equation prediction of the critical compressibility factor, which is $Z_{\text{c}}=3/8=0.375$ .
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] A modified form of the Redlich–Kwong equation was proposed by Soave.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] where *ω* is the acentric factor for the species.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The formulation for $\alpha$ above is actually due to Graboski and Daubert.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] This equation may have up to three roots.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The maximal root of the cubic equation generally corresponds to a vapor state, while the minimal root is for a liquid state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] This should be kept in mind when using cubic equations in calculations, e.g., of vapor-liquid equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Soave replaced the ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {T}}}}$ term of the Redlich–Kwong equation with a function *α*(*T*,*ω*) involving the temperature and the acentric factor (the resulting equation is also known as the Soave–Redlich–Kwong equation of state; SRK EOS).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The *α* function was devised to fit the vapor pressure data of hydrocarbons and the equation does fairly well for these materials.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Note especially that this replacement changes the definition of *a* slightly, as the $T_{\text{c}}$ is now to the second power.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] where $\alpha$ and other parts of the SRK EOS is defined in the SRK EOS section.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] A downside of the SRK EOS, and other cubic EOS, is that the liquid molar volume is significantly less accurate than the gas molar volume.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] where c is an additional fluid component parameter that translates the molar volume slightly.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] On the liquid branch of the EOS, a small change in molar volume corresponds to a large change in pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] On the gas branch of the EOS, a small change in molar volume corresponds to a much smaller change in pressure than for the liquid branch.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Thus, the perturbation of the molar gas volume is small.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Unfortunately, there are two versions that occur in science and industry.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] In the second version both $V_{{\text{m}},{\text{SRK}}}$ and $b_{\text{SRK}}$ are translated, or the translation of $V_{{\text{m}},{\text{SRK}}}$ is followed by a renaming of the composite parameter *b* − *c*.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] A nice feature with the volume translation method of Peneloux et al.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] (1982) is that it does not affect the vapor–liquid equilibrium calculations.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] This method of volume translation can also be applied to other cubic EOSs if the *c*-parameter correlation is adjusted to match the selected EOS.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The model should provide reasonable accuracy near the critical point, particularly for calculations of the compressibility factor and liquid density.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The mixing rules should not employ more than a single binary interaction parameter, which should be independent of temperature, pressure, and composition.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The equation should be applicable to all calculations of all fluid properties in natural gas processes.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] For the most part the Peng–Robinson equation exhibits performance similar to the Soave equation, although it is generally superior in predicting the liquid densities of many materials, especially nonpolar ones.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Detailed performance of the original Peng-Robinson equation has been reported for density, thermal properties, and phase equilibria.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Briefly, the original form exhibits deviations in vapor pressure and phase equilibria that are roughly three times as large as the updated implementations.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The departure functions of the Peng–Robinson equation are given on a separate article.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] A modification to the attraction term in the Peng–Robinson equation of state published by Stryjek and Vera in 1986 (PRSV) significantly improved the model's accuracy by introducing an adjustable pure component parameter and by modifying the polynomial fit of the acentric factor.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] where $\kappa _{1}$ is an adjustable pure component parameter.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Stryjek and Vera published pure component parameters for many compounds of industrial interest in their original journal article.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] At reduced temperatures above 0.7, they recommend to set $\kappa _{1}=0$ and simply use $\kappa =\kappa _{0}$ .
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] For alcohols and water the value of $\kappa _{1}$ may be used up to the critical temperature and set to zero at higher temperatures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] A subsequent modification published in 1986 (PRSV2) further improved the model's accuracy by introducing two additional pure component parameters to the previous attraction term modification.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] where $\kappa _{1}$ , $\kappa _{2}$ , and $\kappa _{3}$ are adjustable pure component parameters.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] PRSV2 is particularly advantageous for VLE calculations.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] While PRSV1 does offer an advantage over the Peng–Robinson model for describing thermodynamic behavior, it is still not accurate enough, in general, for phase equilibrium calculations.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The highly non-linear behavior of phase-equilibrium calculation methods tends to amplify what would otherwise be acceptably small errors.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] It is therefore recommended that PRSV2 be used for equilibrium calculations when applying these models to a design.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] However, once the equilibrium state has been determined, the phase specific thermodynamic values at equilibrium may be determined by one of several simpler models with a reasonable degree of accuracy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] One thing to note is that in the PRSV equation, the parameter fit is done in a particular temperature range which is usually below the critical temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Above the critical temperature, the PRSV alpha function tends to diverge and become arbitrarily large instead of tending towards 0.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Because of this, alternate equations for alpha should be employed above the critical point.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] This is especially important for systems containing hydrogen which is often found at temperatures far above its critical point.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Several alternate formulations have been proposed.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Some well known ones are by Twu et al. and by Mathias and Copeman.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] An extensive treatment of over 1700 compounds using the Twu method has been reported by Jaubert and coworkers.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Detailed performance of the updated Peng-Robinson equation by Jaubert and coworkers has been reported for density, thermal properties, and phase equilibria.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Briefly, the updated form exhibits deviations in vapor pressure and phase equilibria that are roughly a third as large as the original implementation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The attractive force parameter ‘a’ was considered to be a constant with respect to pressure in the Peng–Robinson equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The modification, in which parameter ‘a’ was treated as a variable with respect to pressure for multicomponent multi-phase high density reservoir systems was to improve accuracy in the prediction of properties of complex reservoir fluids for PVT modeling.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The variation was represented with a linear equation where a1 and a2 were the slope and the intercept respectively of the straight line obtained when values of parameter ‘a’ are plotted against pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] This modification increases the accuracy of the Peng–Robinson equation of state for heavier fluids particularly at high pressure ranges (>30MPa) and eliminates the need for tuning the original Peng–Robinson equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Tunning was captured inherently during the modification of the Peng-Robinson Equation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] These works have been published in reputable journals.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The Elliott–Suresh–Donohue (ESD) equation of state was proposed in 1990.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The equation corrects the inaccurate van der Waals repulsive term that is also applied in the Peng–Robinson EOS.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The attractive term includes a contribution that relates to the second virial coefficient of square-well spheres, and also shares some features of the Twu temperature dependence.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The EOS accounts for the effect of the shape of any molecule and can be directly extended to polymers with molecular parameters characterized in terms of solubility parameter and liquid volume instead of using critical properties (as shown here).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The EOS itself was developed through comparisons with computer simulations and should capture the essential physics of size, shape, and hydrogen bonding as inferred from straight chain molecules (like *n*-alkanes).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] and c is a "shape factor", with $c=1$ for spherical molecules.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] (and is hence also equal to 1 for spherical molecules).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The model can be extended to associating components and mixtures with non-associating components.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] In this form, SAFT's segmental perspective is evident and all the results of Michael Wertheim are directly applicable and relatively succinct.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] In SAFT's segmental perspective, each molecule is conceived as comprising *m* spherical segments floating in space with their own spherical interactions, but then corrected for bonding into a tangent sphere chain by the (*m* − 1) term.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] When *m* is not an integer, it is simply considered as an "effective" number of tangent sphere segments.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Solving the equations in Wertheim's theory can be complicated, but simplifications can make their implementation less daunting.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Briefly, a few extra steps are needed to compute $Z^{\rm {assoc}}$ given density and temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] $N_{\text{A}}$ is the Avogadro constant, $K^{\text{AD}}$ and $\epsilon ^{\text{AD}}$ are stored input parameters representing the volume and energy of hydrogen bonding.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] For example, $N^{\text{AD}}$ = 1 for alcohols like methanol and ethanol. $N^{\text{AD}}$ = 2 for water. $N^{\text{AD}}$ = degree of polymerization for polyvinylphenol.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] So you use the density and temperature to calculate $\alpha ^{\text{AD}}$ then use $\alpha ^{\text{AD}}$ to calculate the other quantities.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Technically, the ESD equation is no longer cubic when the association term is included, but no artifacts are introduced so there are only three roots in density.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The extension to efficiently treat any number of electron acceptors (acids) and donors (bases), including mixtures of self-associating, cross-associating, and non-associating compounds, has been presented here.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Detailed performance of the ESD equation has been reported for density, thermal properties, and phase equilibria.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Briefly, the ESD equation exhibits deviations in vapor pressure and vapor-liquid equilibria that are roughly twice as large as the Peng-Robinson form as updated by Jaubert and coworkers, but deviations in liquid-liquid equilibria are roughly 40% smaller.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The cubic-plus-association (CPA) equation of state combines the Soave–Redlich–Kwong equation with the association term from SAFT based on Chapman's extensions and simplifications of a theory of associating molecules due to Michael Wertheim.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The development of the equation began in 1995 as a research project that was funded by Shell, and published in 1996.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] In the association term $X^{\text{A}}$ is the mole fraction of molecules not bonded at site A.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The cubic-plus-chain (CPC) equation of state hybridizes the classical cubic equation of state with the SAFT chain term.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The addition of the chain term allows the model to be capable of capturing the physics of both short-chain and long-chain non-associating components ranging from alkanes to polymers.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The CPC monomer term is not restricted to one classical cubic EOS form, instead many forms can be used within the same framework.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] where $A^{\mathrm {R} }$ is the residual Helmholtz energy, m is the chain length, "rep" and "att" are the monomer repulsive and attractive contributions of the cubic equation of state, respectively.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The "chain" term accounts for the monomer beads bonding contribution from SAFT equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] where A is the molecular interaction energy parameter, B is the co-volume parameter, ${\bar {m}}$ is the mole-average chain length, *g(β)* is the radial distribution function (RDF) evaluated at contact, and *β* is the reduced volume.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The CPC model combines the simplicity and speed compared to other complex models used to model polymers.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Sisco et al. applied the CPC equation of state to model different well-defined and polymer mixtures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] They analyzed different factors including elevated pressure, temperature, solvent types, polydispersity, etc.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] The CPC model proved to be capable of modeling different systems by testing the results with experimental data.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] Alajmi et al. incorporate the short-range soft repulsion to the CPC framework to enhance vapor pressure and liquid density predictions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] They provided a database for more than 50 components from different chemical families, including *n*-alkanes, alkenes, branched alkanes, cycloalkanes, benzene derivatives, gases, etc.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-equations-of-state] This CPC version uses a temperature-dependent co-volume parameter based on perturbation theory to describe short-range soft repulsion between molecules.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] In mathematics, a **cubic function** is a function of the form $f(x)=ax^{3}+bx^{2}+cx+d,$ with ⁠ $a\neq 0$ ⁠, that is, a polynomial function of degree three.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] In many texts, the *coefficients* a, b, c, and d are supposed to be real numbers, and the function is considered as a real function that maps real numbers to real numbers or as a complex function that maps complex numbers to complex numbers.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] In other cases, the coefficients may be complex numbers, and the function is a complex function that has the set of the complex numbers as its codomain, even when the domain is restricted to the real numbers.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] whose solutions are called roots of the function.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] The derivative of a cubic function is a quadratic function.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] A cubic function with real coefficients has either one or three real roots (which may not be distinct); all odd-degree polynomials with real coefficients have at least one real root.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] The graph of a cubic function always has a single inflection point.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] It may have two critical points, a local minimum and a local maximum.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] Otherwise, a cubic function is monotonic.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] The graph of a cubic function is symmetric with respect to its inflection point; that is, it is invariant under a rotation of a half turn around this point.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] Up to an affine transformation, there are only three possible graphs for cubic functions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] Cubic functions are fundamental for cubic interpolation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] The critical points of a cubic function are its stationary points, that is the points where the slope of the function is zero.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] The sign of the expression Δ0 = *b*2 − 3*ac* inside the square root determines the number of critical points.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] If it is positive, then there are two critical points, one is a local maximum, and the other is a local minimum.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] If *b*2 − 3*ac* = 0, then there is only one critical point, which is an inflection point.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] If *b*2 − 3*ac* < 0, then there are no (real) critical points.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] In the two latter cases, that is, if *b*2 − 3*ac* is nonpositive, the cubic function is strictly monotonic.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] See the figure for an example of the case Δ0 > 0.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] The inflection point of a function is where that function changes concavity.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] An inflection point occurs when the second derivative $f''(x)=6ax+2b,$ is zero, and the third derivative is nonzero.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] The graph of a cubic function is a cubic curve, though many cubic curves are not graphs of functions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] Although cubic functions depend on four parameters, their graph can have only very few shapes.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] This similarity can be built as the composition of translations parallel to the coordinates axes, a homothecy (uniform scaling), and, possibly, a reflection (mirror image) with respect to the y-axis.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] This means that there are only three graphs of cubic functions up to an affine transformation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] Firstly, if *a* < 0, the change of variable *x* → −*x* allows supposing *a* > 0.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] After this change of variable, the new graph is the mirror image of the previous one, with respect of the y-axis.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] This corresponds to a translation parallel to the x-axis.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] which is the simplest form that can be obtained by a similarity.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] where $\operatorname {sgn}(p)$ has the value 1 or −1, depending on the sign of p.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] If one defines $\operatorname {sgn}(0)=0,$ the latter form of the function applies to all cases (with $x_{2}=x_{3}$ and $y_{2}=y_{3}$ ).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] For a cubic function of the form $y=x^{3}+px,$ the inflection point is thus the origin.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] As such a function is an odd function, its graph is symmetric with respect to the inflection point, and invariant under a rotation of a half turn around the inflection point.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] As these properties are invariant by similarity, the following is true for all cubic functions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] The tangent lines to the graph of a cubic function at three collinear points intercept the cubic again at collinear points.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] This is an affine transformation that transforms collinear points into collinear points.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] Given the values of a function and its derivative at two points, there is exactly one cubic function that has the same four values, which is called a cubic Hermite spline.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] There are two standard ways for using this fact.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] Firstly, if one knows, for example by physical measurement, the values of a function and its derivative at some sampling points, one can *interpolate* the function with a continuously differentiable function, which is a piecewise cubic function.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] If the value of a function is known at several points, cubic interpolation consists in approximating the function by a continuously differentiable function, which is piecewise cubic.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cubic-function] For having a uniquely defined interpolation, two more constraints must be added, such as the values of the derivatives at the endpoints, or a zero curvature at the endpoints.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Cyclohexane is one of the components of naphtha, from which it can be extracted by advanced distillation methods.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Distillation is usually combined with isomerization of methylcyclopentane, a similar component extracted from naphtha by similar methods.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Together these processes cover only a minority (15-20%) of the modern industrial demand and are complemented by synthesis.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] On an industrial scale, cyclohexane is produced by hydrogenation of benzene in the presence of a Raney nickel catalyst.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Producers of cyclohexane account for approximately 11.4% of global demand for benzene.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The reaction is highly exothermic, with ΔH(500 K) = -216.37 kJ/mol.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Dehydrogenation commenced noticeably above 300 °C, reflecting the favorable entropy for dehydrogenation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Unlike benzene, cyclohexane is not found in natural resources such as coal.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] For this reason, early investigators synthesized their cyclohexane samples.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Surprisingly, their cyclohexanes boiled higher by 10 °C than either hexahydrobenzene or hexanaphthene, but this riddle was solved in 1895 by Markovnikov, N.M.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Kishner, and Nikolay Zelinsky when they reassigned "hexahydrobenzene" and "hexanaphtene" as methylcyclopentane, the result of an unexpected rearrangement reaction.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] (1860–1929) prepared it via a Wurtz reaction of 1,6-dibromohexane.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Although rather unreactive, cyclohexane undergoes autoxidation to give a mixture of cyclohexanone and cyclohexanol.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The cyclohexanone–cyclohexanol mixture, called "*KA oil*", is a raw material for adipic acid and caprolactam, precursors to nylon.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Several million kilograms of cyclohexanone and cyclohexanol are produced annually.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] It is used as a solvent in some brands of correction fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Cyclohexane is sometimes used as a non-polar organic solvent, although n-hexane is more widely used for this purpose.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] It is frequently used as a recrystallization solvent, as many organic compounds exhibit good solubility in hot cyclohexane and poor solubility at low temperatures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Cyclohexane is also used for calibration of differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) instruments, because of a convenient crystal-crystal transition at −87.1 °C.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Cyclohexane vapour is used in vacuum carburizing furnaces, in heat treating equipment manufacture.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The 6-vertex edge ring does not conform to the shape of a perfect hexagon.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The conformation of a flat 2D planar hexagon has considerable strain because the C-H bonds would be eclipsed.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Therefore, to reduce torsional strain, cyclohexane adopts a three-dimensional structure known as the chair conformation, which rapidly interconvert at room temperature via a process known as a chair flip.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] During the chair flip, there are three other intermediate conformations that are encountered: the half-chair, which is the most unstable conformation, the more stable boat conformation, and the twist-boat, which is more stable than the boat but still much less stable than the chair.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The chair and twist-boat are energy minima and are therefore conformers, while the half-chair and the boat are transition states and represent energy maxima.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The idea that the chair conformation is the most stable structure for cyclohexane was first proposed as early as 1890 by Hermann Sachse, but only gained widespread acceptance much later.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The new conformation puts the carbons at an angle of 109.5°.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Half of the hydrogens are in the plane of the ring (*equatorial*) while the other half are perpendicular to the plane (*axial*).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] This conformation allows for the most stable structure of cyclohexane.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Another conformation of cyclohexane exists, known as boat conformation, but it interconverts to the slightly more stable chair formation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] If cyclohexane is mono-substituted with a large substituent, then the substituent will most likely be found attached in an equatorial position, as this is the slightly more stable conformation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Cyclohexane has the lowest angle and torsional strain of all the cycloalkanes; as a result cyclohexane has been deemed a 0 in total ring strain.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The high-temperature phase I, stable between 186 K and the melting point 280 K, is a plastic crystal, which means the molecules retain some rotational degree of freedom.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] The low-temperature (below 186 K) phase II is ordered.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Two other low-temperature (metastable) phases III and IV have been obtained by application of moderate pressures above 30 MPa, where phase IV appears exclusively in deuterated cyclohexane (application of pressure increases the values of all transition temperatures).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/cyclohexane] Here Z is the number structure units per unit cell; the unit cell constants a, b and c were measured at the given temperature T and pressure P.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In physics and chemistry, an **equation of state** is a thermodynamic equation relating state variables, which describe the state of matter under a given set of physical conditions, such as pressure, volume, temperature, or internal energy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Most modern equations of state are formulated in the Helmholtz free energy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Equations of state are useful in describing the properties of pure substances and mixtures in liquids, gases, and solid states as well as the state of matter in the interior of stars.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Though there are many equations of state, none accurately predicts properties of substances under all conditions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The quest for a universal equation of state has spanned three centuries.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] At present, there is no single equation of state that accurately predicts the properties of all substances under all conditions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] An example of an equation of state correlates densities of gases and liquids to temperatures and pressures, known as the ideal gas law, which is roughly accurate for weakly polar gases at low pressures and moderate temperatures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] This equation becomes increasingly inaccurate at higher pressures and lower temperatures, and fails to predict condensation from a gas to a liquid.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] where p is the pressure, V the volume, and T the temperature of the system.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Yet also other variables may be used in that form.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] It is directly related to Gibbs phase rule, that is, the number of independent variables depends on the number of substances and phases in the system.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] An equation used to model this relationship is called an equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In most cases this model will comprise some empirical parameters that are usually adjusted to measurement data.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Equations of state can also describe solids, including the transition of solids from one crystalline state to another.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Equations of state are also used for the modeling of the state of matter in the interior of stars, including neutron stars, dense matter (quark–gluon plasmas) and radiation fields.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] A related concept is the perfect fluid equation of state used in cosmology.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Equations of state are applied in many fields such as process engineering and petroleum industry as well as pharmaceutical industry.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Any consistent set of units may be used, although SI units are preferred.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Absolute temperature refers to the use of the Kelvin (K), with zero being absolute zero.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Boyle's law was one of the earliest formulation of an equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In 1662, the Irish physicist and chemist Robert Boyle performed a series of experiments employing a J-shaped glass tube, which was sealed on one end.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Mercury was added to the tube, trapping a fixed quantity of air in the short, sealed end of the tube.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Then the volume of gas was measured as additional mercury was added to the tube.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The pressure of the gas could be determined by the difference between the mercury level in the short end of the tube and that in the long, open end.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Through these experiments, Boyle noted that the gas volume varied inversely with the pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In mathematical form, this can be stated as: $pV=\mathrm {constant} .$ The above relationship has also been attributed to Edme Mariotte and is sometimes referred to as Mariotte's law.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] However, Mariotte's work was not published until 1676.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In 1787 the French physicist Jacques Charles found that oxygen, nitrogen, hydrogen, carbon dioxide, and air expand to roughly the same extent over the same 80-kelvin interval.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Mathematically, this can be represented for n species as: $p_{\text{total}}=p_{1}+p_{2}+\cdots +p_{n}=\sum _{i=1}^{n}p_{i}.$ In 1834, Émile Clapeyron combined Boyle's law and Charles' law into the first statement of the *ideal gas law*.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Initially, the law was formulated as *pVm* = *R*(*TC* + 267) (with temperature expressed in degrees Celsius), where *R* is the gas constant.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] However, later work revealed that the number should actually be closer to 273.2, and then the Celsius scale was defined with $0~^{\circ }\mathrm {C} =273.15~\mathrm {K}$ , giving: $pV_{m}=R\left(T_{C}+273.15\ {}^{\circ }{\text{C}}\right).$ In 1873, J.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] D. van der Waals introduced the first equation of state derived by the assumption of a finite volume occupied by the constituent molecules.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] His new formula revolutionized the study of equations of state, and was the starting point of cubic equations of state, which most famously continued via the Redlich–Kwong equation of state and the Soave modification of Redlich-Kwong.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] $\left(P+a{\frac {1}{V_{m}^{2}}}\right)(V_{m}-b)=RT$ where a is a parameter describing the attractive energy between particles and b is a parameter describing the volume of the particles.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Since for atomic and molecular gases, the classical ideal gas law is well suited in most cases, let us describe the equation of state for elementary particles with mass m and spin s that takes into account quantum effects.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In the following, the upper sign will always correspond to Fermi–Dirac statistics and the lower sign to Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In the limiting case where $e^{\mu /(k_{\text{B}}T)}\ll 1$ , this equation of state will reduce to that of the classical ideal gas.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The quantum nature of this equation is in its dependence on s and **ħ**.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Cubic equations of state are called such because they can be rewritten as a cubic function of $V_{m}$ .
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Cubic equations of state originated from the van der Waals equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Hence, all cubic equations of state can be considered 'modified van der Waals equation of state'.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] There is a very large number of such cubic equations of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] For process engineering, cubic equations of state are today still highly relevant, e.g. the Peng Robinson equation of state or the Soave Redlich Kwong equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Although usually not the most convenient equation of state, the virial equation is important because it can be derived directly from statistical mechanics.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] This equation is also called the Kamerlingh Onnes equation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] If appropriate assumptions are made about the mathematical form of intermolecular forces, theoretical expressions can be developed for each of the coefficients.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] *A* is the first virial coefficient, which has a constant value of 1 and makes the statement that when volume is large, all fluids behave like ideal gases.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The second virial coefficient *B* corresponds to interactions between pairs of molecules, *C* to triplets, and so on.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Accuracy can be increased indefinitely by considering higher order terms.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The coefficients *B*, *C*, *D*, etc. are functions of temperature only.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Values of the various parameters can be found in reference materials.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The BWR equation of state has also frequently been used for the modelling of the Lennard-Jones fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] There are several extensions and modifications of the classical BWR equation of state available.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Note that in this virial equation, the fourth and fifth virial terms are zero.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The second virial coefficient is monotonically decreasing as temperature is lowered.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The third virial coefficient is monotonically increasing as temperature is lowered.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The Lee–Kesler equation of state is based on the corresponding states principle, and is a modification of the BWR equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] There is a large number of physically based equations of state available today.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Most of those are formulated in the Helmholtz free energy as a function of temperature, density (and for mixtures additionally the composition).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The Helmholtz energy is formulated as a sum of multiple terms modelling different types of molecular interaction or molecular structures, e.g. the formation of chains or dipolar interactions.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Hence, physically based equations of state model the effect of molecular size, attraction and shape as well as hydrogen bonding and polar interactions of fluids.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In general, physically based equations of state give more accurate results than traditional cubic equations of state, especially for systems containing liquids or solids.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Most physically based equations of state are built on monomer term describing the Lennard-Jones fluid or the Mie fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Perturbation theory is frequently used for modelling dispersive interactions in an equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] There is a large number of perturbation theory based equations of state available today, e.g. for the classical Lennard-Jones fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The two most important theories used for these types of equations of state are the Barker-Henderson perturbation theory and the Weeks–Chandler–Andersen perturbation theory.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The SAFT equation of state was developed using statistical mechanical methods (in particular the perturbation theory of Wertheim) to describe the interactions between molecules in a system.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The idea of a SAFT equation of state was first proposed by Chapman et al. in 1988 and 1989.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Many different versions of the SAFT models have been proposed, but all use the same chain and association terms derived by Chapman et al.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Multiparameter equations of state are empirical equations of state that can be used to represent pure fluids with high accuracy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Multiparameter equations of state are empirical correlations of experimental data and are usually formulated in the Helmholtz free energy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The functional form of these models is in most parts not physically motivated.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] They can be usually applied in both liquid and gaseous states.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Empirical multiparameter equations of state represent the Helmholtz energy of the fluid as the sum of ideal gas and residual terms.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The reduced density $\rho _{r}$ and reduced temperature $T_{r}$ are in most cases the critical values for the pure fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Because integration of the multiparameter equations of state is not required and thermodynamic properties can be determined using classical thermodynamic relations, there are few restrictions as to the functional form of the ideal or residual terms.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Typical multiparameter equations of state use upwards of 50 fluid specific parameters, but are able to represent the fluid's properties with high accuracy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Multiparameter equations of state are available currently for about 50 of the most common industrial fluids including refrigerants.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The IAPWS95 reference equation of state for water is also a multiparameter equations of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Mixture models for multiparameter equations of state exist, as well.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Yet, multiparameter equations of state applied to mixtures are known to exhibit artifacts at times.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] One example of such an equation of state is the form proposed by Span and Wagner.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] This is a somewhat simpler form that is intended to be used more in technical applications.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Equations of state that require a higher accuracy use a more complicated form with more terms.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] where e is the internal energy per unit mass, $\gamma$ is an empirically determined constant typically taken to be about 6.1, and $p^{0}$ is another constant, representing the molecular attraction between water molecules.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The magnitude of the correction is about 2 gigapascals (20,000 atmospheres).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The equation is stated in this form because the speed of sound in water is given by $c^{2}=\gamma \left(p+p^{0}\right)/\rho$ .
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] This equation mispredicts the specific heat capacity of water but few simple alternatives are available for severely nonisentropic processes such as strong shocks.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The Landau–Stanyukovich–Zeldovich–Kompaneets equation of state (often abbreviated LSZK EOS) is a thermodynamic model used to describe the pressure–energy relationship of detonation products and high‑pressure reactive gases in computational hydrodynamics and explosive physics.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] It is named after prominent Soviet physicists Lev Landau & K.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Stanyukovich (1945),[1] and Yakov Zeldovich & Alexander Kompaneyets (1960).[2] The LSZK EOS is primarily used to model detonation products rather than the unreacted solid explosive itself.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] It provides a smooth pressure–energy relationship suitable for numerical simulations of blast waves and shock propagation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] where $\gamma$ is the specific heat ratio and $p_{shift}$ is a pressure offset to account for non-ideal behavior of real detonation gases.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] An ultrarelativistic fluid has equation of state $p=\rho _{m}c_{s}^{2}$ where p is the pressure, $\rho _{m}$ is the mass density, and $c_{s}$ is the speed of sound.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The ratio $V=\rho _{e}/\rho$ is defined by using $\rho _{e}$ , which is the density of the explosive (solid part) and $\rho$ , which is the density of the detonation products.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] The parameters A , B , $R_{1}$ , $R_{2}$ and $\omega$ are given by several references.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] In addition, the initial density (solid part) $\rho _{0}$ , speed of detonation $V_{D}$ , Chapman–Jouguet pressure $P_{CJ}$ and the chemical energy per unit volume of the explosive $e_{0}$ are given in such references.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] These parameters are obtained by fitting the JWL-EOS to experimental results.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/equation-of-state] Typical parameters for some explosives are listed in the table below.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In thermodynamics, the **fugacity** of a real gas is an effective partial pressure which replaces the ideal partial pressure in an accurate computation of chemical equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] It is equal to the pressure of an ideal gas which has the same temperature and molar Gibbs free energy (chemical potential) as the real gas.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Fugacities are determined experimentally or estimated from various models such as a Van der Waals gas that are closer to reality than an ideal gas.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] For an ideal gas, fugacity and pressure are equal, and so *φ* = 1.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Taken at the same temperature and pressure, the difference between the molar Gibbs free energies of a real gas and the corresponding ideal gas is equal to *RT* ln *φ*.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The fugacity is closely related to the thermodynamic activity.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] For a gas, the activity is simply the fugacity divided by a reference pressure to give a dimensionless quantity.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] This reference pressure is called the standard state and normally chosen as 1 atmosphere or 1 bar.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Accurate calculations of chemical equilibrium for real gases should use the fugacity rather than the pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The thermodynamic condition for chemical equilibrium is that the total chemical potential of reactants is equal to that of products.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] If the chemical potential of each gas is expressed as a function of fugacity, the equilibrium condition may be transformed into the familiar reaction quotient form (or law of mass action) except that the pressures are replaced by fugacities.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] For a condensed phase (liquid or solid) in equilibrium with its vapor phase, the chemical potential is equal to that of the vapor, and therefore the fugacity is equal to the fugacity of the vapor.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] This fugacity is approximately equal to the vapor pressure when the vapor pressure is not too high.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Fugacity is closely related to the chemical potential *μ*.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In a pure substance, *μ* is equal to the Gibbs energy *G*m for a mole of the substance, and $d\mu =dG_{\mathrm {m} }=-S_{\mathrm {m} }dT+V_{\mathrm {m} }dP,$ where *T* and *P* are the temperature and pressure, *V*m is the volume per mole and *S*m is the entropy per mole.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] For an ideal gas the equation of state can be written as $V_{\mathrm {m} }^{\text{ideal}}={\frac {RT}{P}},$ where *R* is the ideal gas constant.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The differential change of the chemical potential between two states of slightly different pressures but equal temperature (i.e., d*T* = 0) is given by $d\mu =V_{\mathrm {m} }dP=RT\,{\frac {dP}{P}}=RT\,d\ln P,$ where **ln p** is the natural logarithm of p.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In other words, real gases behave like ideal gases at low pressures and high temperatures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] At moderately high pressures, attractive interactions between molecules reduce the pressure compared to the ideal gas law; and at very high pressures, the sizes of the molecules are no longer negligible and repulsive forces between molecules increases the pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] At low temperatures, molecules are more likely to stick together instead of rebounding elastically.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The ideal gas law can still be used to describe the behavior of a real gas if the pressure is replaced by a *fugacity* *f*, defined so that $d\mu =RT\,d\ln f$ and $\lim _{P\to 0}{\frac {f}{P}}=1.$ That is, at low pressures *f* is the same as the pressure, so it has the same units as pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The ratio $\varphi ={\frac {f}{P}}$ is called the *fugacity coefficient*.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] If a reference state is denoted by a zero superscript, then integrating the equation for the chemical potential gives $\mu -\mu ^{0}=RT\,\ln {\frac {f}{P^{0}}},$ Note this can also be expressed with $a=f/P^{0}$ , a dimensionless quantity, called the *activity*.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The contribution of nonideality to the molar Gibbs energy of a real gas is equal to *RT* ln *φ*.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] For nitrogen at 100 atm, *G*m = *G*m,id + *RT* ln 0.9703, which is less than the ideal value *G*m,id because of intermolecular attractive forces.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Finally, the activity is just 97.03 without units.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] When calculating the fugacity of the compressed phase, one can generally assume the volume is constant.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Using *f*sat = *φ*sat *p*sat, where *φ*sat is the fugacity coefficient, $f=\varphi _{\mathrm {sat} }P_{\mathrm {sat} }\exp \left({\frac {V\left(P-P_{\mathrm {sat} }\right)}{RT}}\right).$ This equation allows the fugacity to be calculated using tabulated values for saturated vapor pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Often the pressure is low enough for the vapor phase to be considered an ideal gas, so the fugacity coefficient is approximately equal to 1.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Unless pressures are very high, the Poynting factor is usually small and the exponential term is near 1.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Frequently, the fugacity of the pure liquid is used as a reference state when defining and using mixture activity coefficients.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The fugacity is most useful in mixtures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] It does not add any new information compared to the chemical potential, but it has computational advantages.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] As the molar fraction of a component goes to zero, the chemical potential diverges but the fugacity goes to zero.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In addition, there are natural reference states for fugacity (for example, an ideal gas makes a natural reference state for gas mixtures since the fugacity and pressure converge at low pressure).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The partial pressures obey Dalton's law: $P_{i}=y_{i}P,$ where P is the total pressure and *yi* is the mole fraction of the component (so the partial pressures add up to the total pressure).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The fugacities commonly obey a similar law called the Lewis and Randall rule: $f_{i}=y_{i}f_{i}^{*},$ where *f** *i* is the fugacity that component *i* would have if the entire gas had that composition at the same temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Both laws are expressions of an assumption that the gases behave independently.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In a liquid mixture, the fugacity of each component is equal to that of a vapor component in equilibrium with the liquid.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In an ideal solution, the fugacities obey the Lewis-Randall rule: $f_{i}=x_{i}f_{i}^{*},$ where *xi* is the mole fraction in the liquid and *f*∗ *i* is the fugacity of the pure liquid phase.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] This is a good approximation when the component molecules have similar size, shape and polarity.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In a dilute solution with two components, the component with the larger molar fraction (the solvent) may still obey Raoult's law even if the other component (the solute) has different properties.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] That is because its molecules experience essentially the same environment that they do in the absence of the solute.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] By contrast, each solute molecule is surrounded by solvent molecules, so it obeys a different law known as Henry's law.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] By Henry's law, the fugacity of the solute is proportional to its concentration.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The constant of proportionality (a measured Henry's constant) depends on whether the concentration is represented by the mole fraction, molality or molarity.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The pressure dependence of fugacity (at constant temperature) is given by $\left({\frac {\partial \ln f}{\partial P}}\right)_{T}={\frac {V_{\mathrm {m} }}{RT}}$ and is always positive.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The temperature dependence at constant pressure is $\left({\frac {\partial \ln f}{\partial T}}\right)_{P}={\frac {\Delta H_{\mathrm {m} }}{RT^{2}}},$ where Δ*H*m is the change in molar enthalpy as the gas expands, liquid vaporizes, or solid sublimates into a vacuum.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Also, if the pressure is *P*0, then $\left({\frac {\partial }{\partial T}}\left(T\ln {\frac {f}{P^{0}}}\right)\right)_{P}=-{\frac {S_{\mathrm {m} }}{R}}<0.$ Since the temperature and entropy are positive, ln ⁠*f*/*P*0⁠ decreases with increasing temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The fugacity can be deduced from measurements of volume as a function of pressure at constant temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In that case, $\ln \varphi ={\frac {1}{RT}}\int _{0}^{p}\left(V_{m}-V_{\mathrm {m} }^{\mathrm {ideal} }\right)dP.$ This integral can also be calculated using an equation of state.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Then, to a good approximation, most gases have the same value of *Z* for the same reduced temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] However, in geochemical applications, this principle ceases to be accurate at pressures where metamorphism occurs.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] For a gas obeying the van der Waals equation, the explicit formula for the fugacity coefficient is $RT\ln \varphi ={\frac {RTb}{V_{\mathrm {m} }-b}}-{\frac {2a}{V_{\mathrm {m} }}}-RT\ln \left(1-{\frac {a(V_{\mathrm {m} }-b)}{RTV_{\mathrm {m} }^{2}}}\right)$ This formula is based on the molar volume.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Since the pressure and the molar volume are related through the equation of state; a typical procedure would be to choose a volume, calculate the corresponding pressure, and then evaluate the right-hand side of the equation.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The word *fugacity* is derived from the Latin *fugere*, to flee.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] In the sense of an "escaping tendency", it was introduced to thermodynamics in 1901 by the American chemist Gilbert N.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Lewis and popularized in an influential textbook by Lewis and Merle Randall, *Thermodynamics and the Free Energy of Chemical Substances*, in 1923.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] The "escaping tendency" referred to the flow of matter between phases and played a similar role to that of temperature in heat flow.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] At the time of Lewis' 1901 paper, physical chemistry was primarily based on inexact gas pressure laws, involving vapor pressures and partial pressures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] By replacing these gas pressures with fugacity, Lewis preserved these laws’ mathematical simplicity while accounting for real-world deviations.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Historians argue that Lewis, a young scientist aware of Josiah Willard Gibbs’ rigorous but abstract thermodynamics (including chemical potential), sought to reform the prevailing experimental framework with exact equations that retained practical utility.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/fugacity] Although Lewis’ 1901 paper omitted Gibbs’ formalism entirely, his later works explicitly linked fugacity to chemical potential.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] The easiest thermodynamic models, also known as equations of state, can come from simple correlations that relate different thermodynamic properties using a linear or second-order polynomial function of temperature and pressures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] They are generally fitted using experimental data available for that specific properties.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] This approach can result in limited predictability of the correlation and as a consequence it can be adopted only in a limited operating range.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] By contrast, more advanced thermodynamic models are built in a way that can predict the thermodynamic behavior of the system, even if the functional form of the model is not based on the real thermodynamic behaviour of the material.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] These types of models contain different parameters that are gradually developed for each specific model in order to enhance the accuracy of the evaluating thermodynamic properties.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Cubic equations of state refer to the group of thermodynamic models that can evaluate the specific volume of gas and liquid systems as a function of pressure and temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] To develop a cubic model, first, it is essential to select a cubic functional form.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] The most famous functional forms of this category are Redlich-Kwong, Soave-Redlich-Kwong and Peng-Robinson.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Although their initial form is empirically suggested, they are categorised as semi-empirical models as their parameters can be adjusted to fit the real experimental measurement data of the target system.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] In case the development of a cubic model for a pure component is targeted, the purpose would be to replicate the specific volume behaviour of the fluid in terms of temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] At a given temperature, any cubic functional form results in two separate roots which makes us capable of modelling the behaviour of both vapour and liquid phases within a single model.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Finding the roots of the cubic function will be done by simulating the vapour-liquid equilibrium condition of the pure component where the fugacity coefficients of the two phases are equal to each other.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] So, in this case, the main aim can be limited to deriving fugacity coefficients of vapour and liquid phases from the cubic model and refining the adjustable parameters of the model such that they will become equal to each other at different equilibrium pairs of temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] As the equilibrium pressure and temperature are related together in the case of a pure component system, the functional form of cubic models are able to evaluate the specific volume of the system in the wide range of temperature and pressure domain.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Cubic model development for mixtures of more than one component is different as, according to the Gibbs phase rule, at each temperature level of a multi-component system, equilibrium states can exist at multiple pressure levels.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] *Single phase:* Although a cubic model for a pure component is capable of predicting the specific volume of the system at both vapour and liquid phases, this is not the case for multi-component systems.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Currently cubic models are used for the prediction of specific volume only in the vapour phase, while the liquid phase is modelled with more complex models based on the excess Gibbs energy, such as UNIFAC, UNIQUAQ, etc.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] *Vapour and liquid phases:* Cubic models can be expanded to model multi-component systems at both vapour and liquid phases by integrating a proper mixing rule in their structural function.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Mixing rules refer to different approaches that can be used to modify the cubic model in the case of multi-component mixtures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] The simplest mixing rule is proposed by van der Waals and is called the *van der Waals one fluid (vdW1f)* mixing rule.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] As it can be understood from its name, this mixing rule is only used in case of modelling of a single phase (vapor phase).
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] where $a_{ij}$ and $b_{ij}$ are the parameters of the main target cubic model that was previously chosen.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] In the case of using this mixing rule, except the two adjustable binary interaction parameters (BIPs) for each combination ( $k_{ij}$ and $l_{ij}$ ), other parameters are specified based on the pure component parameters and the concentration of different constituents in the mixture.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] So, the model developed in this case is limited to adjusting these two parameters such that the fugacity coefficients at different phases will be equal to each other at a certain temperature and pressure level.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] To overcome the limitation of the sole single-phase behaviour prediction in the case of using this mixing rule, other advanced mixing rules are developed.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] To predict the thermodynamic behaviour of the multi-component system in different phases, it is essential to build the energy function as a fundamental property of the system.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Although this is mainly the case for the fundamental models, advanced mixing rules such as Huran-Vidal mixing rule and Wong-Sandler mixing rule are developed to adjust the parameters of the cubic models to contain these fundamental properties.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] This is usually done by building a mathematical structure capable of calculating the excess Gibbs energy of the system.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] It is generally built by two widely used approaches, namely UNIFAC and Non Random Two Liquid (NRTL) method.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] The choice of the proper mixing rule to be implemented in the target system can be done based on the inherent properties of the target system such as the polarity of different components, the reactivity of system's constituents with respect to each other, etc.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Fundamental models refer to a family of thermodynamic models that propose a mathematical form for one of the fundamental thermodynamic properties of the system, such as Gibbs free energy or Helmholtz free energy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] For the development of Helmholtz free energy models, the idea is to associate different parameters that resemble different inter-molecular forces between system species.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] As a result, these models are referred to as multi-parameter models.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] *Helmholtz free energy of binary mixtures:* Helmholtz free energy of a multi-component system can be obtained from the weighted sum of the Helmholtz free energy of each binary combination of the system constituents.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] The binary Helmholtz free energy contains different terms that are taking into account various intermolecular forces that can exist based on the inherent of the two target components.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Such models are developed for natural gas components through GERG-2008 thermodynamic model and EOS-CGfor the humid and combustion gas-like mixtures.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] The main advantages of these models are their generality, which makes them applicable to a wide range of pressure, temperature, and the whole concentration range of involved constituents.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] A thermodynamic model predicts different properties with a certain level of accuracy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] In fact, based on the functional form of the thermodynamic model and the real behaviour of the system some properties can be predicted with high accuracy level, while the other ones could not be predicted accurately enough to comply with different industrial needs.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] In this regard several criterions should be taken into account for the proper choice of thermodynamic model to be practical based on the targeted application.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] When a model is targeted to be used in a specific application, the initial step is to identify the temperature and pressure at what the model is intended to be implemented.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] If the model is able to perform in the target operating window, the second step is to investigate whether the model can cover all the system constituents within the concentration ranges of interest or not.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Fundamental models answered this ambiguity by covering the whole concentration range of the compounds that they involved.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] However, this is not the case for ad-hoc cubic model developments which may be considered in the specific range of concentration based on the application.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Thermodynamic models should be robust and reliable, providing consistent results across different conditions and applications.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] They should be able to handle non-ideal behaviour, phase transitions, and complex interactions without significant loss of accuracy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Although some models are capable of taking into account the possible reactions between the system constituents, this is not the case for other simpler models that can only predict the behaviour of the system only in a specific phase.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] So, it is essential to identify the typical behaviour of the fluid in the target application to select and develop a proper model.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] However, in most engineering applications, developing a model that would be able to predict the thermodynamic properties of the system in different phases, critical regions and taking into account the possible reaction between systems is a necessity.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Based on the foundation that each thermodynamic model is built, the accuracy could vary not only for a specific property evaluation from different models but also for predicting different properties within a specific model itself.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Cubic models are developed based on the phase equilibrium and as a result, they can predict the phase equilibrium of pure and multi-component systems within an acceptable accuracy level in case the model is fine-tuned to the experimental data of interest.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] However, this family of models is not accurate enough in predicting density and specific heat capacity as the two main thermodynamic properties that are of importance in most industrial applications.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] In the recent case, some corrections are suggested to enhance the accuracy of the cubic models for different properties, such as Peneloux translation for density prediction.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] On the other hand, models that are developed based on fundamental properties such as Gibbs free energy or Helmholtz free energy, are generally capable of predicting a wider range of properties.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] As these models have a multiple number of adjustable parameters that fitted to different of experimental properties data, it makes them a pioneer when it comes to accuracy.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] The model should be computationally efficient, especially for complex systems and large-scale simulations.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] The model's equations and algorithms should be designed to minimize computational time.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] This is especially important in cases where transient processes are targeted that thermodynamic properties change significantly over the transient time domain and computationally demanding models cannot satisfy industrial needs.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] In certain applications, it may be important to consider the acceptance and implementation of a specific thermodynamic model within the industry.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] Industrial standards and guidelines can provide insights into the preferred models for specific processes.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] However, not all thermodynamic models are widely available in commercial software packages.
[src:thermodynamic-modelling/thermodynamic-modelling] This is especially the case for more complex fundamental models that despite their robustness, they are not still well-accepted by industry to their limited availability.
